After giving this some thought I think we achieve the same thing with less ceremony;

For long running operations have an interface that consists of a pair of methods that allow for starting the operation and checking on its completion along these lines (I imagine in `ClusterManagementService`);
```java
public Long startClusterRebalanceOperation(); // returns unique id for the operation

public SomeResultClass checkClusterRebalanceResult(Long operationId); // SomeResultClass meaningful to specific operation
```
In the implementation I'm expecting to see something along these lines; first a private method to do the long running call and return a `CompletableFuture` object;
```java
private CompletableFuture<SomeResultClass> rebalanceCluster() {
  return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    // all of the following depends on implementation
    SomeResultClass result = new SomeResultClass();
    result.setStartTime(...);
    result.setResult(callToLongRunningRebalanceOperation());
    result.setEndTime(...);
    result.setSuccess(true);
    // other outcomes handled here as well ...
    return result;
  });
}
```

Second the implementation of the public methods that start and check the long running operation;
```java
public Long startClusterRebalanceOperation() {
  CompletableFuture<SomeResultClass> futureResult = rebalanceCluster(); // call to private method
  Long rebalanceId = new Random().nextLong();
  this.clusterRebalanceResultMap.put(rebalanceId, futureResult);
  return rebalanceId;
}

public SomeResultClass checkClusterRebalanceResult(Long operationId) {
  CompletableFuture<SomeResultClass> futureResult = this.clusterRebalanceResultMap.get(rebalanceId);
  // checks, errors omitted
  if(futureResult.isDone()) {
    return futureResult.get();
    // possibly remove from map or keep for history depending on requirements
  } else {
    SomeResultClass result = new SomeResultClass();
    result.setSuccess(false);
    result.setStatus("in_progress");
    return result;
  }
}
```

The `CompletableFuture` will return `false` for `isDone()` as long as the lambda has not returned anything. There are other possible conditions but we have some control over that in case we want to allow for cancelling of operations for example. 

The code is rudimentary and we'd need some synchronization but I think this can do the job.

@onichols-pivotal I don't think I understand the need for the registry. That is based on the (possibly wrong) assumption that we have a limited number of long running operations and simply would declare each in the interface (with appropriate parameters) and implement them in both the `LocatorClusterManagementService` and `ClientClusterManagementService`. 

I think the client code will have some dependencies on shared classes between client and server but I assume that shared code will be part of the management module. 

We can discuss further when you're back.

There are a few existing *StatsTest junit tests (like CachePerfStatsTest). You might add a similar one for ClientStatsTest.

You also might want to take an existing wan dunit test and modify it to test that the ClientStats stats are set properly.

There are a lot of stats in there, but these especially are useful:

- connections
- disconnects
- gatewayBatchs
- pings

You might also want to verify the stats instance is set to the correct type.

The wan dunit tests extend from WANTestBase. One that deals with stats is called ParallelWANStatsDUnitTest. Unfortunately, these tests are pretty complicated. Hopefully, you can just hook into one that is already there.

Here is a method to get the ConnectionStats for a GatewaySender:
```
private void getGatewaySenderConnectionStats(String gatewaySenderId) {
  AbstractGatewaySender sender = (AbstractGatewaySender) CacheFactory.getAnyInstance().getGatewaySender(gatewaySenderId);
  if (sender != null) {
    int totalConnections = 0;
    for (ConnectionStats connectionStats : sender.getProxy().getEndpointManager().getAllStats().values()) {
      totalConnections += connectionStats.getConnections();
    }
    System.out.println("Total connections: " + totalConnections);
  }
}
```

@mivanac Thanks again for another contribution! I'll email the dev list for you to try and encourage some reviews. Please feel free to email the dev list anytime about your PRs.

You could probably tidy up the PR title and the commit messages to encourage more reviews as well. It's kind of hard to know what this PR pertains to without studying the Jira ticket GEODE-6762. This in no way justifies no reviews though!

For git commit messages, we try to follow [Chris Beams' How to Write a Git Commit Message](https://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/). For example, you might squash your commits to: "GEODE-6762: Prevent unnecessary PartitionedRegion callback events". That would probably make a good PR title as well.
